item.title: Director of Tennis: Kirk Shoemaker.
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
<!--more-->
A fixture around the AVCC for more than a decade, Kirkstepped into the director's role on very short notice in winter 2015.
Scant months later, the courts are buzzing with clinics, lessons and doubles games.
Sunday Socials happen once a month. They start in midafternoon, mixingdoubles on the courts with dinner and drinks on the patio outside the dining room.

item.title: The sweet spot for tennis in the Valley.
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
Maybe we've just been having too much fun on the courts to notice, but it's hard to believe we've been aroundfor more than three decades.

Because in the AV, were the place where people love to play.

So, of course, you'll find everything you'd expect at a first-rate tennis club:
  • Five very nicely lit hard courts.
  • Complete locker-room facilities with private showers.
  • The club dining room, with a full liquor license, is available to tennis members.
  • As are the pool and fitness areas.
But more important, you'll find great people to play with and a growing mix of programs and activities to help you develop the best game you've ever had. And it all happens in a relaxed, casual atmosphere that's as much about family fun as it is about winning matches. So if you're looking for a place to play, join the AVCC now.

Already a member?

Check out the latest games and clinics. Or log in andsee who's in the player directory.

item.title: Join the AVCC!
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
You'd think people would have to jump through all kinds of hoops to be a part of allthis great tennis fun:
  • Level ratings.

  • Finding someone to nominate you.

Nope.

All we ask is this: Join the Antelope Valley Country Club as a tennis member. To do that, start here. Then, come back to pick some games and groups. And we'll see you on the courts!

item.title: Join us for Junior clinics!
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
Captain Kirk and companyteach junior clinicsafter schooltwo days a week. Overall, ourphilosophy isthat you can neverspend too much time on the basics: consistent strokes, timely footwork and old-fashioned fun on the court.

Wednesdays.

Ages 11 and up, 4-5:30 pm.
Amore advanced clinic, with focus as much onplanningand winning the point as on refining strokes. Plus:
  • Sportsmanship and empathy.
  • Poiseinwinning - and grace in losing.
  • An ethic of physical and mental fitness.

Thursdays.

Ages 10 and under, 4-5 pm.
Whether your child has never held a racquet or hasbeen playing for several years, Wednesday's clinic has much to teach her:
  • Strokes that make sure she hits the same shot every time.
  • Friendly competition with her own agemates of varying skill levels.
  • Teamwork and empathy.
  • The rules, code and customs of the game.
  • An ethic of overall fitness.

Sign up for spring sessions now.

item.title: Hold your Hand UP!
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
Remember the song?

If you're of a certain age, you remember a band called War, who snag, "Hold your head up." Great advice on the serve, but you also want to hold your hand up. Here's our friend Mark getting ready to volley. On high forehand volleys and on overheads, you'll get more power and placement if you hold your left hand up as you turn to swing - and you'll be less likely to slam the ball into the net. So how does that tune go? Hold your HAND up!
